Effective field theory for resonant wino dark matter

Evan Johnson johnson.6036@osu.edu ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Hong Zhang zhang.5676@osu.edu ‚ÄÉ‚ÄÉ Eric Braaten braaten.1@osu.edu Department of Physics, The Ohio State University, Columbus, OH¬†43210, USA
Abstract

Enhancements in WIMP annihilation rates have been identified with a nonperturbative ‚ÄúSommerfeld enhancement‚Äù arising from the exchange of light mediators. At certain critical values of the WIMP mass, the enhancement is increased dramatically due to a zero-energy resonance at the WIMP-pair threshold. For masses near these critical values, WIMP scattering processes are accurately described by an effective field theory where WIMPs have nonperturbative zero-range contact interactions. The effective field theory is controlled by a renormalization-group fixed point at which the WIMPs are degenerate in mass and their scattering length is infinite. If the WIMPs can exchange massless mediators, the resulting long-range interaction must also be treated nonperturbatively. We develop an effective field theory for S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2)-triplet dark matter, which have short-range weak and long-range electromagnetic interactions. We refer to these dark matter particles as winos. The long-range Coulomb interaction between charged winos is resummed to all orders. The parameters of the effective field theory can be determined by matching wino-wino scattering amplitudes calculated by solving the Schr√∂dinger equation with a potential describing exchange of electroweak gauge bosons. With Coulomb resummation, the effective field theory at leading order gives a good description of the low-energy two-body observables for winos.

‚Ä†‚Ä†preprint: APS/123-QED

I Introduction

Weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) are one of the best motivated candidates for a dark matter particle. Stable particles with weak interactions with masses roughly at the electroweak scale are naturally produced in the early universe and freeze out with a relic abundance comparable to the observed mass density of dark matter Kolb:1990vq ; Steigman:2012nb . If the WIMP mass MùëÄM is in the TeV range, the self-interactions of nonrelativistic WIMPs are complicated by a nonperturbative effect pointed out by Hisano et al. Hisano:2002fk . Exchanges of gauge bosons must be summed to all orders in the gauge coupling constant and can provide a nonperturbative ‚ÄúSommerfeld enhancement‚Äù to low-energy scattering and annihilation cross sections.

For certain critical values of the WIMP mass MùëÄM, the enhancement is increased dramatically due to a zero-energy resonance at the WIMP-pair threshold. When the resonance is in the S-wave channel, the enhancement in WIMP cross sections occurs over a broader range of MùëÄM than in higher partial waves. A feature unique to the S-wave channel is the dynamical generation of a length scale, the scattering length aùëéa, which can be orders of magnitude larger than the range of the weak interactions.

In a fundamental quantum field theory, WIMPs interact through the exchange of gauge bosons through local interactions. The Sommerfeld enhancement can be calculated by summing up an infinite number of gauge boson exchange diagrams. In the Milky Way, WIMPs have velocities on the order of 10-‚Äã3superscript10-310^{\text{-}3} and can be treated nonrelativistically. The exchange of weak gauge bosons becomes nonperturbative for relative momentum below Œ±2‚ÄãMsubscriptùõº2ùëÄ\alpha_{2}M. Photon exchange becomes nonperturbative for relative momentum below Œ±‚ÄãMùõºùëÄ\alpha M. WIMPs with TeV scale masses and relative velocity on the order of 10-‚Äã3superscript10-310^{\text{-}3} therefore have nonperturbative electroweak interactions. This challenge is overcome by solving a Schr√∂dinger equation in which WIMPs interact via instantaneous interactions at a distance through a potential generated by the exchange of electroweak gauge bosons. The Sommerfeld enhancement is determined numerically by solving the Schr√∂dinger equation with this potential. We refer to this framework as nonrelativistic effective field theory (NREFT) and use it as a microscopic description of the WIMP interactions.

Near the critical values of the WIMP mass, the calculation of scattering observables is further facilitated by employing an effective field theory in which WIMPs interact nonperturbativly through contact interactions and charged WIMPs can exchange photons. We refer to this theory as zero-range effective field theory (ZREFT). In Ref.¬†Braaten:2017gpq , we developed the ZREFT for WIMPs that consist of the neutral dark-matter particle w0superscriptùë§0w^{0} and charged WIMPs w+superscriptùë§w^{+} and w‚àísuperscriptùë§w^{-} with a slightly larger mass. We refer to these WIMPs as winos, because the fundamental theory describing them could be the minimal supersymmetric standard model (MSSM) in a region of parameter space where the neutral wino is the lightest supersymmetric particle.

In Ref.¬†Braaten:2017gpq , the ZREFT for winos is developed for winos with short-range weak interactions only. It is shown to be a systematically improvable effective field theory by calculating wino-wino scattering observables to NLO in the ZREFT power counting. We build on the results in Ref.¬†Braaten:2017gpq by including the effects of Coulomb resummation in the interactions between charged winos and show that the theory gives good agreement even at leading order, where there is a single free parameter. This paper serves to summarize the main results of Ref.¬†Braaten:2017kci , presented here without derivation. In Ref.¬†BJZ-Annihilation , we complete the effective field theory by including the effects of wino-pair annihilation into electroweak gauge bosons.

This paper is organized as follows. In Sec.¬†II, we present the fundamental relativistic quantum field theory describing winos and their electroweak interactions. In Sec.¬†III, we describe the nonrelativistic treatment of wino scattering processes by solving a Schr√∂dinger equation. In Sec.¬†IV, we introduce the zero-range model that describes winos with nonperturbative local interactions, and carry out the Coulomb resummation. In Sec.¬†V, we define the zero-range effective field theory by identifying the appropriate renormalization group fixed point and a power counting for perturbations around that fixed point. In Sec.¬†VI, we compare results calculated numerically by solving the Schr√∂digner equation with results calculated analytically in ZREFT at leading order. We conclude in Sec.¬†VII.

II Fundamental theory

We assume the dark-matter particle is the neutral member of an S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) triplet of Majorana fermions with zero hypercharge. The Lorentz-invariant quantum field theory that provides a fundamental description of these fermions could simply be an extension of the Standard Model with this additional S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) multiplet and with a symmetry that forbids the decay of the fermion into Standard Model particles. The fundamental theory could also be the Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model (MSSM) in a region of parameter space where the lightest supersymmetric particle is a wino-like neutralino. In either case, we refer to the particles in the S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) multiplet as winos. We denote the neutral wino by w0superscriptùë§0w^{0} and the charged winos by w+superscriptùë§w^{+} and w‚àísuperscriptùë§w^{-}. For the neutral wino to be a stable dark matter candidate, the masses of the neutral and charged winos must be split by a small amount Œ¥ùõø\delta. In the MSSM, the mass splitting arises from radiative corrections and has a value Œ¥=170ùõø170\delta=170¬†MeV.

The winos can be represented by a triplet of Majorana spinor fields. We will take the neutral wino mass MùëÄM to be an adustable parameter, and we keep the wino mass splitting fixed at Œ¥=170ùõø170\delta=170¬†MeV. The most important interactions of the winos are those with the electroweak gauge bosons: the photon, the W¬±superscriptùëäplus-or-minusW^{\pm}, and the Z0superscriptùëç0Z^{0}. The relevant Standard Model parameters are the mass mW=80.4subscriptùëöùëä80.4m_{W}=80.4¬†GeV of the W¬±superscriptùëäplus-or-minusW^{\pm}, the mass mZ=91.2subscriptùëöùëç91.2m_{Z}=91.2¬†GeV of the Z0superscriptùëç0Z^{0}, the S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) coupling constant Œ±2=1/29.5subscriptùõº2129.5\alpha_{2}=1/29.5, the electromagnetic coupling constant Œ±=1/137.04ùõº1137.04\alpha=1/137.04, and the weak mixing angle, which is given by sin2‚Å°Œ∏W=0.231superscript2subscriptùúÉùëä0.231\sin^{2}\theta_{W}=0.231.

The potential in Eq.¬†(3) can support S-wave resonances at energies dependent on the wino mass MùëÄM. At certain values of the wino mass, there can be a zero-energy resonance at the neutral-wino-pair threshold. IV Zero-Range Model with Coulomb Resummation

The important momentum scales for wino interactions discussed thus far are momentum scales associated with weak exchange: Œ±2‚ÄãMsubscriptùõº2ùëÄ\alpha_{2}M, photon exchange: Œ±‚ÄãMùõºùëÄ\alpha M, and transitions between channels: Œî=2‚ÄãM‚ÄãŒ¥Œî2ùëÄùõø\Delta=\sqrt{2M\delta}. At the unitarity mass M‚àó=2.39subscriptùëÄ2.39M_{*}=2.39¬†TeV, these scales are 81.1¬†GeV, 17.5¬†GeV, and 28.5¬†GeV, respectively. The S-wave resonance at the neutral-wino-pair threshold generates another small momentum scale, the inverse S-wave scattering length Œ≥0subscriptùõæ0\gamma_{0} Braaten:2004rn . The mass dependence of Œ≥0subscriptùõæ0\gamma_{0} is shown in Fig.¬†3. It vanishes at the unitarity mass and its absolute value remains smaller than mWsubscriptùëöùëäm_{W}, the inverse range of weak interactions, for wino mass in the range 1.75‚àí4.61.754.61.75-4.6¬†TeV. In this range, wino interactions can be described by zero-range contact interactions and long-range electromagnetic interctions. The contact and long-range interactions must be treated nonperturbativly in order to generate the small momentum scale Œ≥0subscriptùõæ0\gamma_{0}.

A simple nonrelativistic field theory for low-energy winos with local interactions is the zero-range model introduced in Ref.¬†Braaten:2017gpq . The winos are described by nonrelativistic two-component spinor fields w0subscriptùë§0w_{0}, w+subscriptùë§w_{+}, and w‚àísubscriptùë§w_{-} that annihilate w0superscriptùë§0w^{0}, w+superscriptùë§w^{+}, and w‚àísuperscriptùë§w^{-}, respectively. They can be identified with the fields Œ∂ùúÅ\zeta, Œæ‚Ä†superscriptùúâ‚Ä†\xi^{\dagger}, and Œ∑ùúÇ\eta in NREFT, respectively. The kinetic terms for winos in the Lagrangian for the zero-range model are

The matrix ùìês‚Äã(E)subscriptùìêùë†ùê∏\bm{\mathcal{A}}_{s}(E) in Eq.¬†(17) is a matrix of short-distance transition amplitudes. V ZREFT with Coulomb resummation

The zero-range model with transition amplitudes given by the matrix in Eq.¬†(17) has two coupled scattering channels with different energy thresholds. An effective field theory can be defined most rigorously by identifying a renormalization-group fixed point. Systematically improving accuracy is then ensured by adding to the Lagrangian operators with increasingly higher scaling dimensions.

More convienently, the matrix ùú∏ùú∏\bm{\gamma} in Eq.¬†(25) can be expressed as a power series in p2superscriptùëù2p^{2} with coefficients that define scattering parameters. Systematic improvement can be achieved if we can identify a power counting that determines the improvement in the accuracy of a model that can be obtained by including each of the parameters. To define the power counting, we introduce the generic momentum scale QùëÑQ described by the effective theory. We take the energy Eùê∏E and the mass splitting Œ¥ùõø\delta to be of order Q2/MsuperscriptùëÑ2ùëÄQ^{2}/M. We also introduce a momentum scale ŒõŒõ\Lambda that can be regarded as the ultraviolet cutoff of the effective field theory. The physical interpretation of ŒõŒõ\Lambda is the smallest momentum scale beyond the domain of applicability of the effective field theory. In the case of winos, ŒõŒõ\Lambda is the inverse range mWsubscriptùëöùëäm_{W} of the weak interactions. The power-counting scheme identifies how each parameter scales as a power of QùëÑQ and ŒõŒõ\Lambda. The transition amplitudes ùíúi‚Äãj‚Äã(E)subscriptùíúùëñùëóùê∏\mathcal{A}_{ij}(E) can be expanded in powers of Q/ŒõùëÑŒõQ/\Lambda. The systematically improving accuracy of the effective field theory is ensured by including parameters whose leading contributions to ùíúi‚Äãj‚Äã(E)subscriptùíúùëñùëóùê∏\mathcal{A}_{ij}(E) scale with increasingly higher powers of Q/ŒõùëÑŒõQ/\Lambda.

V.1 Renormalization-group fixed points

Lensky and Birse have carried out a careful renormalization-group (RG) analysis of the two-particle sector for the field theory with two coupled scattering channels with zero-range interactions Lensky:2011he . Three distinct RG fixed points were identified corresponding to zero, one, or two resonances at the scattering threshold. For wino scattering, the appropriate fixed point has a single resonance, and we refer to it as the single-channel-unitarity fixed point. At this fixed point, the two scattering channels have the same threshold (Œ¥=0ùõø0\delta=0), and are mixed by an angle œïitalic-œï\phi. There is nontrivial scattering in a single channel that is a linear combination of the neutral channel w0‚Äãw0superscriptùë§0superscriptùë§0w^{0}w^{0} and the charged channel w+‚Äãw‚àísuperscriptùë§superscriptùë§w^{+}w^{-} with mixing angle œïitalic-œï\phi. In that channel, the cross section saturates the S-wave unitarity bound. There is no scattering in the orthogonal channel. The single-channel-unitarity fixed point is the most natural one for describing a system with a single fine tuning, such as the tuning of the wino mass MùëÄM to a unitarity value where there is an S-wave resonance at the threshold.

At the fixed point, there is a single relevant operator with scaling dimension ‚àí11-1. It corresponds to the parameter c00(u)subscriptsuperscriptùëêùë¢00c^{(u)}_{00} in the coefficient of ùìüu‚Äã(œï)subscriptùìüùë¢italic-œï\bm{\mathcal{P}}_{u}(\phi) in Eq.¬†(V.2). Thus the parameter c00(m)subscriptsuperscriptùëêùëö00c^{(m)}_{00} can be absorbed into the mixing angle œïitalic-œï\phi. All the other operators are irrelevant operators with scaling dimensions 1 or higher. The corresponding parameters can be treated perturbatively. The sums in Eq.¬†(V.2) can be truncated to include only terms with scaling dimensions below some maximum. This truncation defines a field theory with a finite number of parameters. By increasing the maximum scaling dimension, we obtain a systematically improvable sequence of field theories. They define an effective field theory that we refer to as zero-range effective field theory (ZREFT).

If we consider winos with a fixed mass splitting Œ¥ùõø\delta, the momentum scale associated with transitions between the neutral and charged channels is also fixed. Thus the coefficients in each of the sums in Eq.¬†(V.2) with i=0ùëñ0i=0 are not distinguishable and can be absorbed into the coefficients of the powers of p2superscriptùëù2p^{2}. Wino-wino cross sections are calculated in NREFT from Eqs.¬†(5) and in ZREFT from Eqs.¬†(41). The mixing angle is determined by matching the effective range using the result in Eq.¬†(47). The charged wino S-wave elastic cross section œÉ1‚Üí1subscriptùúé‚Üí11\sigma_{1\to 1} also displays oscillations in the center-of-mass energy Eùê∏E. VII Conclusions

The Standard Model does not contain a particle that can compose the dark matter. Models of dark matter are thus models of physics beyond the Standard Model. One of the most natural ways to extend the Standard Model to include possible dark matter particles is to introduce new multiplets of the Standard Model gauge groups along with some symmetry that forbids their decay into Standard Model particles. One possibility is to introduce an S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) triplet with zero hypercharge so that one component is electrically neutral and can play the role of dark matter. Such an extension is already included in models of supersymmetry where the new S‚ÄãU‚Äã(2)ùëÜùëà2SU(2) triplet is the wino. The neutral wino w0superscriptùë§0w^{0} has mass MùëÄM while the charged winos w+superscriptùë§w^{+} and w‚àísuperscriptùë§w^{-} have mass M+Œ¥ùëÄùõøM+\delta, where Œ¥‚â™Mmuch-less-thanùõøùëÄ\delta\ll M. Winos are charged under the electroweak interactions, which are nonperturbative when MùëÄM is in the TeV range. This presents a calculational difficulty in the fundamental quantum field theory describing winos. Exchanges of weak gauge bosons in wino-wino scattering and annihilation must be summed to all orders in Œ±2subscriptùõº2\alpha_{2}. Photon exchange must be summed to all orders in Œ±ùõº\alpha.

One way around these difficulties is by employing the framework of nonrelativistic effective field theory (NREFT) in which winos interact through a weak-interaction potential and in which charged winos also interact by exchanging photons. Cross sections and annihilation rates can be determined by the numerical solution of a Schr√∂dinger equation with a potential arrising from the exchange of weak gauge bosons and photons. At certain values of the wino mass, scattering cross sections and annihilation rates are enhanced by orders of magnitude, as shown in Fig.¬†1. This ‚ÄúSommerfeld enhancement‚Äù occurs because there is a zero-energy resonance at the neutral wino threshold. Near these resonances, the neutral wino S-wave scattering length a0subscriptùëé0a_{0} is much larger than the range 1/mW1subscriptùëöùëä1/m_{W} of the weak interactions, diverging at the resonance. The inverse S-wave scattering length Œ≥0=1/a0subscriptùõæ01subscriptùëé0\gamma_{0}=1/a_{0} is shown as a function of the wino mass in Fig.¬†3. Exactly at the resonance, the neutral-wino S-wave elastic cross section saturates the unitarity bound in Eq.¬†(7a) as E‚Üí0‚Üíùê∏0E\to 0. We refer to these masses as unitarity masses. This large length scale can be exploited by using an effective field theory in which winos interact through nonperturbative contact interactions and charged winos also interact by exchanging photons. We refer to this theory as zero-range effective field theory (ZREFT). The electromagnetic interaction between charged winos must be treated nonperturbatively by summing up photon exchange to all orders.

ZREFT is applicable in a range of MùëÄM where a0>1/mWsubscriptùëé01subscriptùëöùëäa_{0}>1/m_{W} and for winos with relative momentum less than mWsubscriptùëöùëäm_{W}. This inequality holds near unitarity masses M‚àósubscriptùëÄM_{*} where a0subscriptùëé0a_{0} diverges. The first unitarity mass is M‚àó=2.39subscriptùëÄ2.39M_{*}=2.39¬†TeV. The range of MùëÄM where a0>1/mWsubscriptùëé01subscriptùëöùëäa_{0}>1/m_{W}, and thus ZREFT is applicable, is 1.75‚àí4.61.754.61.75-4.6¬†TeV.

While NREFT can describe nonrelativistic winos with any mass MùëÄM, ZREFT has distinct advantages. Two body observables can be calculated analytically in ZREFT and are described very well at leading order in the ZREFT power counting. The matrix of transition amplitudes for wino-wino scattering is presented at leading order in Eq.¬†(40). It has a single free parameter, a mixing angle œïitalic-œï\phi. The mixing angle is determined by the matching condition in Eq.¬†(47). The left hand side of Eq.¬†(47) is the neutral-wino effective range r0subscriptùëü0r_{0}. It is shown as a function of the wino mass in Fig.¬†4 along with an accurate Pad√© approximation which is given in Eq.¬†(LABEL:eq:r0Pade). Using the Pad√© approximation, the mixing angle can be determined over the range in MùëÄM where ZREFT is applicable. The dependence of the mixing angle on MùëÄM is shown in the left panel of Fig.¬†7. The prediction for the neutral-wino shape parameter s0subscriptùë†0s_{0} is shown in the right panel of Fig.¬†7. Using the mass dependent mixing angle, ZREFT gives a good approximation for s0subscriptùë†0s_{0}.

At unitarity masses where the S-wave scattering length diverges, the elastic cross sections have the most dramatic energy dependence. The neutral-wino S-wave elastic cross section is shown in Fig.¬†8. The prediction from ZREFT at leading order agrees very well with the result calculated numerically by solving the Schr√∂dinger equation. An enlargement of the energy region near the charged-wino-pair threshold E=2‚ÄãŒ¥ùê∏2ùõøE=2\delta is shown in the left panel of Fig.¬†9. The ZREFT result reproduces the dramatic resonances in the S-wave elastic cross section. The charged-wino S-wave elastic cross section is reproduced qualitatively by the ZREFT leading order result, as shown in the right panel of Fig.¬†9. The prediction displays the same rapid oscillations found from the numerical result, but with an amplitude smaller by about 40%.

One of the primary motivations for the development of ZREFT for winos was the ‚ÄúSommerfeld enhancement‚Äù of the annihilation of a pair of neutral winos into electroweak gauge bosons. Wino-pair annihilation not only provides additional wino-wino scattering channels, but also affects other aspects of the few-body physics for low-energy winos. The effects of wino-pair annihilation are usually suppressed by Œ±22‚ÄãmW2/M2superscriptsubscriptùõº22superscriptsubscriptùëöùëä2superscriptùëÄ2\alpha_{2}^{2}m_{W}^{2}/M^{2}, which is roughly 10‚àí6superscript10610^{-6} for MùëÄM in the TeV region, but they can be dramatic near a unitarity mass. For example, the neutral-wino elastic cross section does not actually diverge at a unitarity mass, but instead has a very narrow peak as a function of MùëÄM Blum:2016nrz . The finite maximum cross section comes from unitarization of the wino-pair annihilation, which has not been taken into account in most previous calculations of the Sommerfeld enhancement factor. A naive estimate of the maximum cross section is 6 orders of magnitude higher than the cross section above the charged-wino pair threshold. The effects of wino-pair annihilation on low-energy winos can be taken into account in ZREFT by analytically continuing real interaction parameters to complex values. ZREFT can be used to provide analytic results for low-energy wino-wino cross sections and for inclusive wino-pair annihilation rates, including the effects of the unitarization of wino-pair annihilation. The results will be presented in Re.¬†BJZ-Annihilation .
